                    "company": "Leiden University",
                    "description": "Hox genes are an evolutionarily well-conserved family of genes in metazoan animals that have a crucial role in many developmental processes. However, about the conservation of Hox gene patterns across the animal kingdom, much is still unknown. During my project, I visualised and analysed the embryonic expression patterns of sense and antisense Hoxa11 in the limbs of several amniotic species. My main aim was to determine the level of conservation and whether their similarity is correlated with phylogenetic relatedness.\n\nTechniques used: digoxigenin probe synthesis, embryo preparation and whole-mount in situ hybridisation.",
